window.LOGI={"core": [{"key": "arrival-rio", "title": "Arrival in Rio: GIG/Galeão airport to Copacabana/Ipanema beach base", "segments": [{"from": "Long-haul international flight (Europe/US/connections)", "to": "Rio de Janeiro–Galeão / Antônio Carlos Jobim (GIG)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "Effectively ALL intercontinental flights land at GIG (Galeão), ~20km north of the South Zone. Santos Dumont (SDU) is the small downtown airport and handles domestic + a handful of regional South-American shuttle routes only (no long-haul). If your group books an internal connection via São Paulo, you'd likely still arrive into GIG on the Rio leg, though some domestic legs use SDU — check your specific ticket.", "duration": "n/a (arrival point)", "cost": "n/a", "tip": "Confirm GIG vs SDU on each boarding pass. The two airports are ~15km apart and a mix-up at the taxi rank is an expensive mistake. Immigration/baggage at GIG can take 45-90 min on a busy morning bank of arrivals."}, {"from": "GIG arrivals hall (Terminal 2 international)", "to": "Copacabana / Ipanema hotel door", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "Pre-booked private transfer (Welcome Pickups, Daytours4u, Kiwitaxi, or a hotel car). For 5 men with luggage a single large van/minivan (Sprinter/Spin) is the sensible option — meet-and-greet inside the hall, fixed price, no negotiation. Typical fixed van fare ~R$220-330 total, i.e. ~R$45-66 pp.", "duration": "40-60 min (with intl arrivals processing buffer, plan 60-75 min)", "cost": "£7-10 pp", "tip": "Book ONE van rather than two cars — splits cheaper per head and keeps the group together. Give the driver your hotel name, not just 'Copacabana'."}, {"from": "GIG official taxi rank (Terminal 2, ground level)", "to": "Copacabana / Ipanema", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Official airport radio-taxi co-ops (Transcoopass / Cootramo) sell a FIXED-price voucher at a counter before you exit. Copacabana ~R$130-190 per car; ordinary metered street taxis run ~R$120-160. One car holds 4 pax + bags, so 5 men = 2 cars.", "duration": "30-50 min", "cost": "£10-15 pp (across 2 cars)", "tip": "Only use the official counter inside; ignore anyone approaching you in the hall offering a 'taxi' — that's the classic GIG overcharge scam."}, {"from": "GIG designated rideshare pickup zone", "to": "Copacabana / Ipanema", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Uber or 99 (Brazil's local app). To Copacabana ~R$50-90 per car, plus a flat ~R$4.95 airport surcharge; typically 30-40% cheaper than official taxis. 5 men = 2 standard cars, or order one UberXL/van. Pickup is a signed zone a short walk from arrivals.", "duration": "30-50 min", "cost": "£4-8 pp (across 2 cars)", "tip": "Have a Brazilian eSIM/data live before you land so you can summon the car; airport free WiFi is patchy at the curb. UberXL is great value for splitting between 5."}, {"from": "GIG (Terminal 1 door H / Terminal 2 door D)", "to": "Copacabana / Ipanema via Vicente de Carvalho metro interchange", "mode": "bus", "detail": "BRT TransCarioca (24h) to Vicente de Carvalho, then Metro Line 1/2 down to Cardeal Arcoverde/Siqueira Campos (Copacabana) or Nossa Senhora da Paz (Ipanema). Needs a RioCard Mais (buy at station machine, cash/debit). Alternatively the LECD71 premium shuttle runs Galeão→Leblon (~R$24.85) passing through Copa/Ipanema, but only ~06:45-20:15.", "duration": "75-110 min", "cost": "£1-4 pp", "tip": "Cheapest but slow and luggage-unfriendly with a metro transfer — only worth it solo/budget. For a group of 5 just-landed and jet-lagged, skip it."}], "total": "Door-to-door ~1h30-1h45 from wheels-down to hotel check-in (45-90 min arrivals processing + 40-50 min transfer)", "cost": "£4-10 pp by car (Uber/99 cheapest, private van most convenient); ~£10-15 pp by official taxi; ~£1-4 pp by BRT+metro", "frequency": "GIG operates 24h; Uber/99 and BRT available round the clock. Official taxi counters and the LECD71 Leblon shuttle (~06:45-20:15) keep daytime hours. Most long-haul flights from Europe land early-to-mid morning, so expect peak immigration queues and morning traffic into the South Zone.", "tips": ["Book the private van in advance (Welcome Pickups / Daytours4u) with a Portuguese-name flag and your hotel address — for a first arrival with 5 people and bags this removes all curbside friction.", "Set up a Brazilian eSIM (Claro/Vivo, or an international roaming plan) BEFORE landing so Uber/99 and maps work at the curb — this single step unlocks the cheapest options.", "Install the 99 app as a backup to Uber; in Rio 99 is often cheaper and has more cars at the airport, and prices are shown upfront in both."], "gotchas": ["Touts inside the GIG arrivals hall offering 'taxi/transfer' routinely overcharge tourists 2-3x — only use the official taxi counter or a pre-booked named driver.", "GIG (international) and SDU (downtown domestic) are different airports ~15km apart; if any of the group routes via a domestic São Paulo connection, double-check which Rio airport that leg actually lands at.", "The BRT TransCarioca does NOT reach the Zona Sul directly — it forces a metro transfer at Vicente de Carvalho, which is awkward with luggage and not worth it for a tired group of five."], "recommend": "All 5 land at GIG — pre-book ONE private meet-and-greet van (~£7-10 pp) for the jet-lagged first arrival; on later/return trips just split an UberXL (~£4-8 pp)."}, {"key": "rio-ilha", "title": "Rio de Janeiro → Abraão (Ilha Grande)", "segments": [{"from": "Rio hotel (Copacabana/Ipanema/Centro)", "to": "Conceição de Jacareí pier", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "Easy Transfer Brazil shared van with hotel pickup; one-way ~R$130-150 (£20-23). Also bookable via Bookaway/GetYourGuide/Viator. Departs Rio ~08:00 and ~12:00; door-to-pier road leg ~2h30-3h via BR-101. This is the most popular option for groups as it bundles van+boat and sorts the timing for you.", "duration": "2h30-3h00", "cost": "£20-23", "tip": "Book the van+boat combo together so you arrive at the pier matched to a boat slot; confirm pickup window on WhatsApp the day before, as Rio traffic pickup loops add time."}, {"from": "Conceição de Jacareí pier", "to": "Vila do Abraão (Ilha Grande)", "mode": "ferry", "detail": "Flexboat/lancha (fast covered boat) across the channel, run by local operators (e.g. via travessiailhagrande.com). Crossing R$80-150 (£12-23) depending on season; ~20-25 min, the shortest sea crossing. Departures roughly hourly 07:30-18:30. If you booked Easy Transfer the boat ticket is already included in the ~£20-23 above.", "duration": "20-25 min", "cost": "£12-23 (included if via Easy Transfer)", "tip": "Buy a flexboat not the slow schooner if you want speed; the small private flexboats run on demand and won't leave you stranded like the once-daily CCR ferries."}], "total": "Door-to-door roughly 4 hours (3h road + ~30 min boat + buffer/check-in). Easy Transfer advertises a 4h total.", "cost": "£20-25 pp via Easy Transfer combo (van + included boat). DIY (Costa Verde bus + separate flexboat) ~£10-12 pp but much more hassle.", "frequency": "Easy Transfer vans leave Rio ~08:00 and ~12:00 daily. Conceição de Jacareí flexboats run roughly hourly 07:30-18:30 (last ~18:30). Beware the cheap CCR Barcas slow ferries: only ONE per day each (Angra dep ~15:30 weekdays/13:30 weekends, Mangaratiba dep ~08:00) — easy to miss.", "tips": ["Book Easy Transfer direct (their site/WhatsApp) or via Bookaway/GetYourGuide a few days ahead; for a group of 5 reserve together so you're on the same van and boat.", "Always book Conceição de Jacareí (not Angra or Mangaratiba) for the connection — it has the most frequent boats and the 20-min crossing; Angra/Mangaratiba have only one cheap CCR ferry a day.", "Confirm the exact Rio hotel pickup time on WhatsApp the day before; give all 5 names/hotels so the van routes pickups efficiently."], "gotchas": ["The R$20.70 CCR Barcas ferry is the cheapest but runs only once daily from Angra (~15:30) and Mangaratiba (~08:00) — miss it and you're stuck overnight on the mainland. Not viable for a fixed group itinerary.", "Last flexboats from Conceição de Jacareí to Abraão are around 18:00-18:30; a late Rio departure or BR-101 traffic can make you miss the day's last crossing.", "Ilha Grande has no cars and limited ATMs/card coverage at the pier — carry small R$ cash for the boat/porters, and pack light as you'll wheel bags over cobbles in Abraão."], "recommend": "Five men with luggage: book the Easy Transfer van+flexboat combo to Conceição de Jacareí (~£20-25pp door-to-Abraão, ~4h) — fastest crossing, hotel pickup, no timing gambles."}, {"key": "ilha-foz", "title": "Ilha Grande → Foz do Iguaçu (IGU): same-day boat + drive + flight", "segments": [{"from": "Vila do Abraão (Ilha Grande)", "to": "Conceição de Jacareí (mainland port)", "mode": "boat", "detail": "Flexboat / Travessia Ilha Grande speedboat (operators: Flexboat, Travessia Ilha Grande, Porto Real Turismo). Crossing 20-25 min. First useful departures from Abraão side ~08:00-08:30; book the earliest slot. CCR Barcas car-ferry to Angra is cheaper (~R$20) but slower and farther from Rio, so for a same-day flight use the Conceição speedboat.", "duration": "25-35 min (incl. boarding)", "cost": "£12-23 (R$80-150)", "tip": "Pick Conceição de Jacareí, NOT Angra dos Reis — Conceição is ~45 min closer to Rio by road. Pre-book the first morning boat the night before; counters open early but holiday queues are real."}, {"from": "Conceição de Jacareí", "to": "Rio de Janeiro – Galeão Intl Airport (GIG)", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "Private van/transfer along the BR-101 Costa Verde highway, ~120-135 km. For 5 men one van is ideal (Civitatis/Suntransfers/MyTransfers run this; ~US$70-90 per van total). Public Costa Verde bus to Rodoviária Novo Rio + onward to GIG also exists but is 4h+ and too slow for a same-day flight.", "duration": "2h15-2h45 (traffic dependent)", "cost": "£11-14 pp (≈£60-75 per van split 5 ways)", "tip": "Book a private van, not the bus — splitting one van across 5 men is cheap per head and saves ~1.5h. Leave a buffer: BR-101 + Rio entry traffic is unpredictable."}, {"from": "Rio de Janeiro (GIG)", "to": "Foz do Iguaçu (IGU)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "GOL or LATAM operate limited nonstops (~2h15); Azul and most GOL/LATAM services connect via São Paulo–Guarulhos (GRU), Campinas (VCP) or Curitiba (CWB), making it 4-6h total. Earliest LATAM nonstop ~12:20, GOL afternoon from ~13:40. Realistically you catch an early-afternoon departure.", "duration": "2h15 nonstop / 4-6h connecting", "cost": "£25-55 (R$160-360 one-way)", "tip": "Fly from GIG (Galeão), not SDU (Santos Dumont) — IGU service runs out of GIG. Hold out for a nonstop; a connection through GRU can land you in Foz near midnight."}], "total": "~10-13 hours door-to-door (Abraão ~08:00 → Foz ~18:00-21:00), longer if the flight connects", "cost": "£48-92 pp (typical ~£70 pp)", "frequency": "Boats off the island run roughly hourly from early morning; the binding constraint is the flight. GIG–IGU has ~76 morning flights/week but few true nonstops — earliest practical same-day departures are ~12:20-14:00, landing late afternoon/evening.", "tips": ["Book the GIG-IGU flight first and work backwards — let the flight's departure time dictate which morning boat and van pickup you need.", "Pre-book the earliest Abraão→Conceição Flexboat (Travessia Ilha Grande / Flexboat / Porto Real) the night before; don't rely on walk-up during holidays/weekends.", "Arrange one private van for all 5 from the Conceição pier to GIG (Civitatis/Suntransfers/MyTransfers) — cheaper per head than the bus and ~1.5h faster."], "gotchas": ["Most 'RIO–IGU' fares are connecting flights via GRU/CWB/VCP (4-6h) — an unwary booking can land you in Foz near midnight and effectively kill the same-day plan.", "Flights to IGU leave from GIG (Galeão), not the downtown SDU airport — routing your van to the wrong airport is a trip-ender.", "BR-101 Costa Verde traffic and any sea/weather delay on the boat compounds; with no slack you can miss the only suitable nonstop, so build in a 1-2h airport buffer."], "recommend": "Doable as a long single day IF you take the first ~08:00 Flexboat to Conceição, a pre-booked private van to GIG, and a NONSTOP early-afternoon GOL/LATAM flight — but it's tight, so only attempt with a nonstop; if you can only get a connecting flight, overnight in Rio and fly the next morning instead."}, {"key": "iguazu-border", "title": "Foz do Iguaçu (Brazil) to the Argentine side of Iguazú Falls — border crossing", "segments": [{"from": "Your Foz do Iguaçu hotel", "to": "Brazil exit immigration (Ponte Tancredo Neves / BR-277 border post)", "mode": "private transfer / tour van", "detail": "Prearranged private transfer or full-day tour with hotel pickup (operators: Loumar Turismo, Iguassu Secret Garden-recommended drivers, or GetYourGuide/Viator listings). The driver knows the process and WAITS while all 5 of you get the Brazilian exit stamp. ~12-15 km / 20-25 min to the bridge.", "duration": "20-30 min", "cost": "£12-18 pp (private 4x4/van split across 5; ~R$400-550 round-trip total for the vehicle)", "tip": "Book a vehicle that fits 5 + comfortably — a standard sedan taxi only seats 4, so ask for a van/SUV or you'll need two cars."}, {"from": "Brazil immigration (Brazilian side of Tancredo Neves bridge)", "to": "Argentina entry immigration (Argentine side of the bridge)", "mode": "private transfer (same vehicle) across the international bridge", "detail": "Cross the Iguaçu River bridge. Two separate stops: get the Brazil EXIT stamp, then the Argentina ENTRY stamp. UK passport holders need NO visa for either country (90 days visa-free each). Have passports in hand; the driver waits at both posts.", "duration": "20-60 min (queue-dependent; up to 1.5-2 hrs in Dec-Feb high season)", "cost": "included in transfer above", "tip": "Both stamps matter — if you skip the Brazilian exit stamp you can get fined/hassled when you leave Brazil later. Insist the driver stops at BOTH offices, not just drives through."}, {"from": "Argentine border post (Puerto Iguazú side)", "to": "Parque Nacional Iguazú entrance gate (Argentine falls)", "mode": "private transfer (same vehicle)", "detail": "~20 km onward through/past Puerto Iguazú to the park gate. Park entry for non-resident foreigners is ~ARS 45,000 (~£26-30 pp) paid separately at the gate, cash or card. Inside, the free Rainforest Ecological Train runs to Garganta del Diablo.", "duration": "25-35 min", "cost": "transfer included; park ticket ~£26-30 pp extra (not part of crossing)", "tip": "Buy the park ticket online in advance (iguazuargentina.com) to skip the gate queue; bring a card — peso cash is hard to get at a fair rate."}], "total": "Roughly 1.5-2.5 hours each way door-to-door (hotel to Argentine park gate), depending on immigration queues; budget a full day for the visit.", "cost": "~£12-18 pp for the round-trip private transfer/border crossing itself (5-way split). Add ~£26-30 pp for the Argentine park entrance. So ~£40-48 pp all-in for the day if you DIY the transfer, or ~£35-55 pp for a guided full-day tour (transfer + guide, park ticket usually still extra).", "frequency": "Private transfers/tours run daily, on your schedule. Park opens ~08:00-08:30, last entry ~16:00-16:30, closes ~18:00. The cheaper public option (Río Uruguay / Crucero del Norte cross-border buses from Foz's international terminal) runs every ~20-30 min but does NOT reliably wait at Brazilian immigration — you get off, stamp, and flag the next bus, which eats time.", "tips": ["Book the private transfer the day before through your hotel or a reputable agency (Loumar Turismo, or GetYourGuide/Viator 'Argentina side private transfer' listings) and confirm a 5+ seat vehicle and that the driver WAITS at both border posts.", "Pre-purchase Argentine park tickets at iguazuargentina.com (non-resident 'extranjero' rate) to skip the gate line — the price floats with peso inflation so check it close to travel.", "Go early (aim to be at the park gate by 08:30) to beat both the immigration queues and the midday crowds at Garganta del Diablo."], "gotchas": ["The cross-border PUBLIC buses do not wait at Brazilian immigration — you must tell the driver 'Brasil imigração', get off to stamp, then catch the next bus with the same company's ticket. Convenient on paper, slow in practice; a private transfer avoids this entirely.", "Don't skip the Brazil exit stamp. Locals get waved through, so an inexperienced driver may roll past — you need the exit stamp or you risk a fine/delay when you later leave Brazil.", "Argentina is one hour BEHIND Brazil (no DST sync). Factor the time change so you don't misjudge the park's last-entry and closing times.", "ARS park fee fluctuates heavily with inflation (recently ~ARS 35,000-45,000); carry a card and don't rely on getting pesos cheaply at the border."], "recommend": "For 5 men, book a private van/SUV transfer with a driver who waits at both immigration posts (~£12-18 pp split) and pre-buy Argentine park tickets online — fastest, hassle-free, and barely more than the fiddly public bus."}, {"key": "foz-manaus", "title": "Foz do Iguaçu (IGU) → Manaus (MAO): one-stop via São Paulo/Brasília", "segments": [{"from": "Foz do Iguaçu hotel/centre", "to": "Cataratas Intl Airport (IGU)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Uber/99 or official airport taxi; IGU is ~17 km from the city", "duration": "20-30 min", "cost": "£7-12", "tip": "Uber/99 averages ~R$42 (~£6.50); official taxi flat ~R$80 (~£12). Split a single Uber XL across the 5 of you to save."}, {"from": "Foz do Iguaçu (IGU)", "to": "Hub: São Paulo (GRU) or Brasília (BSB)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "LATAM/GOL/Azul to GRU (most frequent, ~1h45-2h); LATAM also to BSB direct. Azul routes via Viracopos (VCP) or Campinas/Confins (CNF).", "duration": "1h45-2h15", "cost": "included in through-fare", "tip": "GRU is the highest-frequency hub for this route; pick a through-ticket so missed-connection risk is on the airline, not you."}, {"from": "Hub (GRU / BSB)", "to": "Manaus (MAO)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "GOL or LATAM fly GRU→MAO and BSB→MAO; both daily. GRU→MAO leg is ~4h.", "duration": "3h45-4h15 (plus 1h15-3h layover)", "cost": "included in through-fare", "tip": "Layover varies hugely (1h15 tight to 3h+). Book a single LATAM or GOL itinerary so the bags check straight through to MAO."}, {"from": "Eduardo Gomes Intl Airport (MAO)", "to": "Manaus city / hotel or river pier", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Uber/99 or official taxi; MAO is ~13 km from centre. Local bus exists (~R$2.75) but 40 min and not luggage-friendly for 5 men.", "duration": "20 min", "cost": "£5-7", "tip": "Taxi ~R$40 (~£6). If you're heading straight to an Amazon lodge boat, confirm the pier (Marina/Manaus Moderna) before you land."}], "total": "Roughly 8-12 hours door-to-door (best one-stop ~6h flying + ~2h layover + airport transfers/check-in); long-layover itineraries can run 13h+.", "cost": "~£150-200 pp one-way (flights ~£140-185 + ~£15 in transfers). Fares seen: LATAM from R$636 (~£98), Azul from R$820 (~£126); realistic booked one-way R$900-1,200 (~£140-185).", "frequency": "Daily on all three carriers. LATAM has by far the most connecting options (~430 connecting flights/week IGU-MAO), GOL ~200/week, Azul ~135/week. Azul (~53% of bookings) and LATAM (~47%) dominate the route. GRU and BSB hubs together feed ~31% of all MAO arrivals.", "tips": ["Book ~5-6 weeks out (min 32 days) for the lowest fares; this is a thin route so last-minute prices spike fast.", "Buy ONE through-ticket (LATAM or GOL) rather than two separate IGU→hub and hub→MAO tickets - through-fares protect your connection and check bags straight to MAO.", "Compare LATAM/GOL via GRU against Azul via VCP/CNF on Google Flights for the same dates; for 5 seats together, lock it early as award/cheap fare buckets sell out per-flight."], "gotchas": ["No direct flight exists - every option is at least one stop, so a tight 1h15 layover at GRU/BSB is risky with 5 people and checked bags; favour a 1h45-2h+ connection.", "Azul itineraries sometimes connect through Viracopos (VCP/Campinas) or Confins (CNF), NOT GRU - don't assume the hub is São Paulo Guarulhos; check the airport code before booking onward ground transport.", "Manaus is the gateway to Amazon lodges - if a boat transfer is pre-booked, build in extra MAO buffer; a long hub layover can push your arrival past the lodge's last-departure pickup time."], "recommend": "Book a single through-ticket on LATAM (or GOL) via GRU São Paulo - most frequent, cheapest base fares (~R$636/£98), and one itinerary means the airline owns any missed-connection risk for all 5 of you."}, {"key": "manaus-lodge", "title": "Manaus airport to Amazon jungle lodge (Juma Amazon Lodge, road + boat combo)", "segments": [{"from": "Manaus airport (MAO) / city hotel", "to": "CEASA harbour, Manaus", "mode": "private transfer (van/car)", "detail": "Lodge-arranged pickup at the airport or your Manaus hotel; morning pickup window 06:30-07:30, afternoon departure ~13:30. Driver consolidates the group and shuttles to the river port. Run by Juma Amazon Lodge's own transfer operation.", "duration": "30-45 min", "cost": "Included in lodge package (£0 marginal)", "tip": "All 5 of you should be on the same package so you ride together; confirm the morning slot to maximise daylight on arrival."}, {"from": "CEASA harbour, Manaus", "to": "Porto Careiro (Careiro village)", "mode": "speedboat", "detail": "Lodge speedboat across the Rio Negro/Solimoes, passing the 'Meeting of the Waters' where the two rivers run side by side before becoming the Amazon. Scenic leg, doubles as a sightseeing stop.", "duration": "45 min", "cost": "Included in lodge package (£0 marginal)", "tip": "Sit on the right side leaving Manaus for the best Meeting of the Waters view; keep cameras in a dry bag, there is spray."}, {"from": "Porto Careiro", "to": "Parana do Mamori (river put-in)", "mode": "private transfer (van)", "detail": "Overland van leg on the south bank through the Careiro da Varzea area to the next boat launch. Roads can be rough/muddy in the wet season (Dec-May).", "duration": "~60 min", "cost": "Included in lodge package (£0 marginal)", "tip": "Bathroom stop here is your last reliable one before the lodge; use it."}, {"from": "Parana do Mamori", "to": "Juma Amazon Lodge (Juma Lake)", "mode": "boat", "detail": "Second motorboat leg up Juma Lake/igarapes to the stilted lodge. Final scenic stretch with good chance of birds and pink-river-dolphin sightings.", "duration": "~60 min", "cost": "Included in lodge package (£0 marginal)", "tip": "In low-water season the boat may be smaller/slower; pack light as bags are hand-loaded between vessels."}], "total": "Approximately 3 to 3.5 hours door-to-door (airport to lodge)", "cost": "£0 marginal — the full road+boat transfer is bundled into the lodge package (typical 3-day/2-night full-board package runs ~R$2,500-3,500pp, i.e. ~£385-£540pp). Optional seaplane upgrade ~R$10,000 (~£1,540) each way for up to 8 people, i.e. ~£385pp split across 5.", "frequency": "Two scheduled group departures daily from Manaus: a morning pickup 06:30-07:30 and an afternoon departure ~13:30 from the airport. Returns reach Manaus around midday. Departures are fixed and shared, not on-demand.", "tips": ["Book direct with the lodge (jumalodge.com.br) or via a Manaus operator (Amazonas by Viverde / Manaus Amazing Tours) and give exact flight times so they slot you into the matching morning or afternoon transfer.", "Get the included transfer confirmed in writing for all 5 names on one package so you travel as one group and aren't split across departures.", "If you want the 35-min seaplane instead, arrange and pay it directly with the air-taxi partner the lodge nominates — it's outsourced, paid to the provider, with no lodge discount."], "gotchas": ["The transfer is timed to fixed daily departures, not your flight — land in Manaus the night before or on an early flight, or you'll miss the morning boat and lose a day.", "Multiple hand-loaded vessel/van changes mean hard-shell or oversized luggage is a pain; bring soft duffels and store excess bags at your Manaus hotel.", "Wet season (Dec-May) makes the overland van leg slower and muddier and can shift timings; the 'Juma' route is south of Manaus (Autazes direction) — don't confuse it with Anavilhanas/Novo Airao, which is a ~3hr paved-road drive north instead."], "recommend": "Book the standard road+boat transfer bundled with a Juma Amazon Lodge package on the morning departure — it's free, scenic (Meeting of the Waters), and gets all 5 of you to the lodge in ~3 hours; only pay for the seaplane if you're time-poor."}, {"key": "manaus-sp", "title": "Manaus (MAO) → São Paulo Guarulhos (GRU) — direct flight home", "segments": [{"from": "Manaus hotel / Centro", "to": "Manaus Eduardo Gomes Intl Airport (MAO)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Metered city taxi or app (Uber/99). Airport is ~14 km north of Centro.", "duration": "20-30 min", "cost": "£6-8 (R$40-50)", "tip": "Use 99 or Uber rather than the airport taxi rank — roughly half the price. For 5 men plus bags, order an XL/Comfort (still under £12). Leave ~30 min buffer for Manaus traffic."}, {"from": "Manaus Airport (MAO)", "to": "São Paulo Guarulhos (GRU)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "Direct non-stop on LATAM, GOL or Azul (B737 / A320 family). LATAM ~28 direct/week, GOL ~14/week, plus Azul. Some Azul/LATAM fares route via CGH or VCP or add a stop — filter for non-stop GRU.", "duration": "~4h 10m (3h55-4h15 airborne)", "cost": "£62-100 one-way (R$404 GOL / R$451 Azul / R$483 LATAM cheapest; mid-fares R$545-595)", "tip": "Book GRU specifically if connecting onward internationally — GOL/Azul cheap fares sometimes land at Congonhas (CGH) or Viracopos (VCP, in Campinas, 100 km out), which wrecks an onward connection."}, {"from": "São Paulo Guarulhos (GRU)", "to": "São Paulo city / onward", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "If GRU is the final/home airport, exit is immediate. Airport bus (Airport Bus Service) or app car into the city.", "duration": "45-70 min to city", "cost": "£0-18 (R$0-120 depending on mode)", "tip": "Only relevant if continuing into São Paulo; if GRU is the home/departure hub for an international leg, no transfer needed."}], "total": "~5 to 5.5 hours door-to-door (30 min taxi + 2h check-in/security + 4h10 flight), excluding any GRU arrival transfer", "cost": "£70-110 pp (flight £62-100 + Manaus taxi ~£2 pp shared)", "frequency": "High frequency: ~30-40 direct flights per week between the three carriers, departures spread 07:35-23:30 daily. Effectively several non-stop options every day.", "tips": ["Book 4-8 weeks out: cheapest one-ways sit around R$404-483 (£62-74); buying late or for weekend departures pushes fares to R$1,000+ (£150+).", "Compare on Google Flights / Kayak then book direct on gol.com.br, latam.com or voeazul.com.br to avoid OTA service fees and easier changes. Brazilian domestic fares are often cheaper on the .com.br sites paid in BRL.", "For 5 passengers, book as one party so the airline seats you together and you split one airport taxi; basic fares usually include only a personal item, so add checked bags up front (much cheaper than at the airport)."], "gotchas": ["São Paulo has THREE airports — GRU (Guarulhos, international hub), CGH (Congonhas, central) and VCP (Viracopos/Campinas, ~100 km away). Cheap GOL/Azul fares sometimes land at CGH or VCP; if you need GRU for an international connection, filter explicitly for MAO→GRU non-stop.", "Manaus is in the Amazonas time zone (UTC-4), one hour behind São Paulo (UTC-3). A 4h10 flight will show ~5h10 on the clock — easy to misread connection times.", "Not every advertised 'Manaus-São Paulo' fare is non-stop; some Azul itineraries make one or two stops (e.g. via Brasília/Campinas) and balloon to 6-9h. Verify the leg is truly direct before booking."], "recommend": "Fly the direct LATAM or GOL non-stop MAO→GRU (~4h10, £62-100 pp); book early, confirm the SP airport is GRU not CGH/VCP, and share one 99/Uber XL to Manaus airport."}, {"key": "sp-departure", "title": "São Paulo (centre/Paulista) → GRU Guarulhos airport for international departure", "segments": [{"from": "Hotel (central SP / Av. Paulista area)", "to": "GRU Airport Terminal 3 (international) curb", "mode": "Uber/99 (private car)", "detail": "Primary recommended option for 5 men with luggage: book 2x UberX or 1x UberXL + 1x UberX (XL seats up to 6 but luggage forces a second car). Average SP→GRU fare ~R$94, realistically R$80-140 per car depending on traffic/surge. 99 app is usually a touch cheaper than Uber. Use the in-app 'GRU Terminal 3 desembarque/embarque' pin.", "duration": "40-60 min (30 min off-peak, 75-90 min in rush hour)", "cost": "~£14-22 pp (two cars ≈ R$180-260 total ÷ 5; budget £18 pp)", "tip": "Split into two cars and leave together; share live trip links so the group stays in convoy. Avoid 7-10am and 5-8pm departures when the Marginal/Ayrton Senna road clogs and surge spikes."}, {"from": "Av. Paulista / Praça da República", "to": "GRU Terminals 1, 2 & 3", "mode": "Airport Bus Service (executive coach)", "detail": "Operator: Airport Bus Service (EMTU concession). Lines serve Av. Paulista, Praça da República, Itaim Bibi, Barra Funda and Congonhas. Fare ~R$46.50-65 depending on line/promo. Buy at the kiosk (cash/card) or airportbusservice.com.br. Air-con, luggage hold, drops at all 3 terminals.", "duration": "50-80 min", "cost": "~£8-10 pp (R$50-65)", "tip": "Good budget pick but departures are roughly every 30-60 min and it makes stops — add buffer. Confirm the line stops nearest your hotel before boarding."}, {"from": "Luz / Barra Funda / Brás (CPTM rail)", "to": "GRU Airport station + free Aeromóvel people-mover to terminals", "mode": "CPTM Line 13-Jade train (Airport Express)", "detail": "Cheapest option. Take metro/CPTM to a Line 13 interchange (Engenheiro Goulart, or Brás/Luz/Barra Funda on the Airport Express), ride Line 13-Jade to Aeroporto-Guarulhos station, then the free Aeromóvel people-mover to Terminals 1/2/3. Integrated fare ~R$5.00 (no special ticket).", "duration": "60-90 min door-to-door incl. connections", "cost": "~£1 pp (R$5)", "tip": "Trains run ~hourly for the Airport Express (departures at :05/:20/:35/:50 past the hour), roughly 5am-midnight. Cheap but with 5 men + bags and a flight to catch, only use if you have lots of time and light luggage."}], "total": "Plan for ~4.5-5 hrs before the flight pushes back: ~1 hr door-to-airport (Uber, with traffic buffer) + 3-3.5 hrs at the airport for international check-in, immigration and security.", "cost": "~£18 pp by Uber/99 (two cars). Bus ~£9 pp; train ~£1 pp.", "frequency": "Uber/99: on-demand 24/7. Airport Bus Service: ~every 30-60 min, roughly 06:00-21:30. CPTM Line 13-Jade Airport Express: ~hourly (:05/:20/:35/:50), ~05:00-midnight; free Aeromóvel people-mover connects the station to all terminals.", "tips": ["GRU has three terminals — international long-haul departures are almost always Terminal 3; tell the driver/bus 'Terminal 3 embarque' to avoid a long walk between terminals.", "For Uber/99, pre-book or order both cars at the same moment so the group leaves together; keep cash/Pix as backup since card-on-file can occasionally fail in-app.", "Airport Bus Service tickets can be bought online in advance at airportbusservice.com.br if you want a guaranteed seat with luggage."], "gotchas": ["Traffic to Guarulhos is wildly variable — the same trip is 30 min off-peak but 90 min in rush hour or rain; never assume the 'average' 46 min when a flight is on the line.", "Terminal 2 (and busy periods generally) can have slow security/immigration queues — add 30 min if departing at peak; 3 hrs minimum for an international flight, ideally 3.5.", "The cheap CPTM train + Aeromóvel is great value but the people-mover/airport-station setup has had phased/limited operating hours in 2025 — verify it's running for your departure time before relying on it."], "recommend": "Book two Uber/99 cars from the hotel ~4.5 hours before departure (5 hrs if leaving in rush hour) — fastest, door-to-door, ~£18 pp split five ways, and no luggage stress."}], "alt": [{"key": "rio-paraty", "title": "Rio de Janeiro to Paraty (Costa Verde bus vs private van)", "segments": [{"from": "Rio hotel (Copacabana/Ipanema)", "to": "Novo Rio Bus Terminal (Rodoviaria Novo Rio)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Uber/99 app, 5 men means 2 cars or one XL/van. ~R$50-70 per car total, ~20-40 min depending on traffic. Cheaper local Real Auto Onibus line 2017 runs from the beach zone for R$6-8 but is slow with luggage.", "duration": "20-40 min", "cost": "£2-3 pp", "tip": "Use the 99 app rather than street taxis; book an early slot and pad time for Rio traffic, the terminal is north of the centre."}, {"from": "Novo Rio Bus Terminal", "to": "Paraty Rodoviaria", "mode": "bus", "detail": "Costa Verde Transportes direct coach (the dominant operator on this route; Buzios Transfer/Top Transfer also run some slots). One-way ~R$130-200 depending on date/demand. Comfortable a/c coach, ~159 km / 99 mi but a winding coastal road.", "duration": "4h30-4h50", "cost": "£20-31 pp", "tip": "Book the leito/executivo class if available and grab seats on the LEFT side outbound for sea views; arrive 30 min early to print/collect the e-ticket."}, {"from": "Paraty Rodoviaria", "to": "Paraty pousada (historic centre)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Terminal is ~1 km from the cobbled old town. Short taxi or 15-min walk; taxis wait at the terminal.", "duration": "5-15 min", "cost": "£1-2 pp", "tip": "The historic centre is pedestrianised cobblestone, so confirm your pousada allows vehicle drop-off nearby or be ready to wheel bags over uneven stones."}], "total": "5.5-6 hours door-to-door by bus (including transfers and terminal waits); ~4.5-5 hours by private van door-to-door", "cost": "~£24-36 pp by bus (transfers + ticket); ~£24-30 pp by private van split across 5", "frequency": "Costa Verde runs frequently: roughly 16 (Sat) to 40+ (weekday) departures daily, first bus ~04:00, last ~23:00. The 07:00-09:00 morning slots are most popular and busiest. Private vans run 24/7 on demand.", "tips": ["Buy Costa Verde tickets in advance online (Busbud, ClickBus, or buscaonibus) for weekends/high season; the popular morning departures sell out and at the counter you may queue.", "For the private van, get a per-vehicle quote from Kiwitaxi or Daytrip (priced per vehicle, not per person) and request a single minivan for 5 plus luggage rather than two sedans.", "Pay attention to where the van picks up: confirm your Rio hotel and exact Paraty pousada addresses at booking so drop-off is at the door, not the terminal."], "gotchas": ["Prices on Kiwitaxi/Daytrip are PER VEHICLE within a capacity class, not per person, so check the van seats 5 plus bags before assuming the quoted price is split-friendly.", "The coastal BR-101 (Rio-Santos) road is winding and prone to landslides/closures in summer rains (Dec-Mar); journeys can run longer than 4h30 and occasionally reroute.", "Paraty's historic centre is car-free cobblestone, so neither bus nor van drops you literally at the pousada door inside the old town, expect a short walk or porter over rough stones."], "recommend": "For 5 men splitting one private van (~R$775-900 / £120-140 per vehicle = ~£24-28 pp), the door-to-door pickup beats the bus on convenience for nearly the same per-person cost; book the Costa Verde bus only if you want the cheapest fixed fare or travel as a flexible pair."}, {"key": "rio-buzios", "title": "Rio de Janeiro → Búzios (Armação dos Búzios)", "segments": [{"from": "Rio hotel (Zona Sul: Copacabana/Ipanema)", "to": "Rodoviária Novo Rio bus terminal", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Uber/99 or taxi to Novo Rio terminal (Santo Cristo). The 1001 bus to Búzios leaves ONLY from Novo Rio, not from Zona Sul.", "duration": "25-45 min (traffic dependent)", "cost": "£5-9 (R$35-60 for the car, ~£1-2 pp split 5 ways but usually 2 cars)", "tip": "Budget extra time in rush hour; the run from Ipanema can hit 45+ min. Two Ubers for 5 men + bags is realistic."}, {"from": "Rodoviária Novo Rio", "to": "Búzios bus terminal (Estrada da Usina)", "mode": "bus", "detail": "Viação 1001 (Auto Viação 1001), Executivo class, A/C, reclining seats, toilet, USB/WiFi on newer coaches. ~9 departures/day.", "duration": "~3h 0m–3h 50m", "cost": "£14 (R$90.59 executivo; book-ahead promos from ~R$55 / £8.50)", "tip": "Book on autoviacao1001.com.br or ClickBus; print/screenshot the QR ticket. Sit on the right for coastal views on the final stretch."}, {"from": "Búzios bus terminal", "to": "Búzios hotel/pousada (Centro, Orla Bardot, Geribá)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Local taxi or van from the rodoviária; central pousadas are 5-15 min away.", "duration": "5-20 min", "cost": "£3-5 (R$20-35 per car)", "tip": "Many central pousadas are walkable, but with luggage grab a taxi — there's a fixed-rate taxi stand at the terminal."}], "total": "~4h 30m – 5h door-to-door (bus option)", "cost": "~£20-25 pp (bus route, all legs)", "frequency": "Viação 1001 runs ~9 departures/day, roughly 06:00 to 20:30 (first ~06:04, last ~20:34). Aggregators list up to dozens of daily Rio–Búzios options including indirect routings. No need to pre-book days ahead except on holidays/long weekends.", "tips": ["Book the 1001 bus via the official site autoviacao1001.com.br or ClickBus/Buson — advance fares drop to ~R$55 (£8.50) vs R$90 walk-up.", "For the door-to-door alternative, CentralBuzios, Daytrip, or Green Toad Bus offer shared shuttles (~R$130-160 / £20-25 pp) and private vans; CentralBuzios confirms hotel pickup time ~24h ahead, usually after 5pm the day before.", "If flying into GIG (Galeão), there are direct 1001 buses Galeão→Búzios — skip going into the city centre entirely if you land and head straight out."], "gotchas": ["The 1001 Búzios bus departs from Rodoviária Novo Rio only — NOT from Copacabana/Ipanema. Factor in the cross-city taxi, which can be slow in traffic.", "Quoted bus time is ~3h but real-world is often 3h30-3h50 with the toll-road traffic and the stop; don't book tight onward plans.", "Private 'per person' transfer prices online (e.g. $90+/USD pp on Viator/GetYourGuide) are pricey for solo travellers — for a group of 5, book the whole VEHICLE (private van) and split it, which is much cheaper per head."], "recommend": "For 5 men on a budget, take the 1001 Executivo bus from Novo Rio (~£14 pp, ~3-3.5h) — but if you'd rather skip the cross-town schlep to Novo Rio and the terminal-to-hotel taxi, a private door-to-door transfer split 5 ways (~R$700-850 total ≈ £22-26 pp) is barely more expensive and far more comfortable."}, {"key": "rio-arraial", "title": "Rio de Janeiro → Arraial do Cabo (Região dos Lagos)", "segments": [{"from": "Hotel in Zona Sul (Copacabana/Ipanema)", "to": "Rodoviária Novo Rio (Av. Francisco Bicalho 1, Santo Cristo, Centro)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Uber/99 or yellow comum taxi. Uber from Zona Sul ~R$50-90; metered comum taxi R$60-90; radio-taxi fixed ~R$130. One car holds 4, so 5 men = 1 UberXL/van or 2 cars.", "duration": "30-50 min (traffic-dependent; allow 60 min in rush hour)", "cost": "~£3-5 pp (one UberXL ~R$90-120 split 5; or 2 cars)", "tip": "Book one UberXL/Comfort for the group. At Novo Rio the Uber pickup is the covered Uber Lounge on floor G1 (2nd floor, follow signs across the walkway) - drivers won't stop kerbside out front."}, {"from": "Rodoviária Novo Rio", "to": "Terminal Rodoviário de Arraial do Cabo (city centre, taxi stand out front)", "mode": "bus", "detail": "Auto Viação 1001 direct service (convencional, air-conditioned). Rio departures approx 05:03 / 09:03 / 12:34 / 15:02 (some routes via Niterói/Araruama/Praia Seca). Fare R$83.93 (cheapest 1001) up to ~R$199 for peak/executivo.", "duration": "3h 30m-3h 50m (122 km; fastest ~2h55, slower routes via Iguaba up to 4h26)", "cost": "~£13 pp (R$84) typical; up to ~£30 pp peak/last-minute", "tip": "Take a DIRECT 1001 service to Arraial do Cabo terminal - some cheaper tickets actually terminate in Cabo Frio (next town, ~15 min away) and you'd need a local connection. Confirm destination is 'Arraial do Cabo' not 'Cabo Frio'."}], "total": "~4.5-5.5 hours door-to-door", "cost": "~£16-20 pp by bus (taxi to terminal + 1001 ticket); ~£50-56 pp if you instead book a private door-to-door van", "frequency": "1001 runs several direct departures daily, roughly every 3-4 hours (approx 05:00, 09:00, 12:30, 15:00 from Rio); last useful direct departure mid-afternoon, so leave Rio in the morning. ~19 connections/day exist if you count routes via Cabo Frio/Iguaba with a change.", "tips": ["Book the 1001 ticket in advance via the Auto Viação 1001 app, ClickBus, or Busbud - summer/long-weekend departures (Arraial is a top beach destination) sell out and last-minute fares jump toward R$200.", "Buy 5 seats together in one transaction so the group isn't split across departures; pick seats on booking.", "For a private van, get quotes from operators like Chofix, Daytrip, or Central Búzios - a van for 5 runs ~R$1500-1800 (~£230-280) total; confirm it's a vehicle for 5+luggage, not a sedan."], "gotchas": ["Cabo Frio vs Arraial do Cabo: cheap/fast tickets often go to Cabo Frio terminal, NOT Arraial - they're different towns ~15-20 min apart. Verify the final stop before buying.", "Novo Rio terminal is in Centro, an area to be cautious in - keep bags close, use the official Uber Lounge (G1), and don't wander; arrive ~30-40 min before departure.", "Friday-afternoon and holiday outbound traffic from Rio toward Região dos Lagos can add 1-2 hours; travel mid-morning or midweek if possible."], "recommend": "Best value for 5 men: one UberXL to Novo Rio + direct Auto Viação 1001 bus to Arraial do Cabo (~£16-20 pp, ~5h). If you have heavy luggage, an early start, or want to skip the terminal, split a private van (~£50-56 pp door-to-door, ~3-3.5h) - convenient but ~3x the price."}, {"key": "reach-chapada", "title": "Reach Chapada Diamantina via Salvador (to Lençóis or Vale do Capão)", "segments": [{"from": "Home / arrival city in Brazil", "to": "Salvador (SSA, Dep. Luís Eduardo Magalhães Airport)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "Domestic flight to Salvador on LATAM, GOL or Azul (hubs: Rio GIG/SDU, São Paulo GRU/CGH, Recife, Brasília). SSA is the main gateway for Chapada.", "duration": "1h30-3h depending on origin (e.g. ~2h from São Paulo, ~2h15 from Rio)", "cost": "£40-£90 pp one-way if booked ~6-8 weeks ahead (R$260-R$580)", "tip": "Book the earliest possible Salvador arrival so you can catch a same-day bus/transfer onward; avoid landing after ~14:00 or you risk an overnight in Salvador."}, {"from": "Salvador airport (SSA)", "to": "Salvador Rodoviária (bus terminal, Pernambués, Av. ACM 4362)", "mode": "taxi", "detail": "Taxi or app (Uber/99) from airport to the rodoviária; ~20 km. Only needed if taking the public bus (skip entirely if doing a door-to-door private transfer).", "duration": "30-50 min depending on traffic", "cost": "£7-£12 pp if split between 5 (total R$120-R$220 / car; may need 2 cars or an XL)", "tip": "Use the 99/Uber app rather than airport rank taxis to avoid being overcharged; for 5 men with bags request a Comfort/XL or take two cars."}, {"from": "Salvador Rodoviária", "to": "Lençóis (Chapada gateway town)", "mode": "bus", "detail": "Real Expresso (also branded Guanabara) is the main operator; Rápido Federal also runs it. Semi-leito (semi-reclining) coach, ~3 departures/day.", "duration": "6h-7h (425 km via BR-324 / BR-242)", "cost": "£20-£24 pp (R$130-R$155 one-way; cheapest seen ~R$143 on Rápido Federal 08:00)", "tip": "Book online via realexpresso.com.br, ClickBus or Busbud a few days ahead in high season; daytime departure (e.g. 08:00) lets you see scenery and arrive before dark."}, {"from": "Lençóis rodoviária", "to": "Final pousada in Lençóis OR onward to Vale do Capão", "detail": "If staying in Lençóis: short taxi/walk in town. If headed to Vale do Capão: the bus does NOT go there directly — you continue to Palmeiras then take a local car/van the last ~20-23 km of dirt road, OR ask your pousada to arrange pickup.", "mode": "private transfer", "duration": "Lençóis town: 5-10 min. Lençóis→Vale do Capão: ~1h30-2h (≈70 km)", "cost": "In-town taxi ~£2-£4 pp; Vale do Capão final leg from Palmeiras ~£3-£6 pp by shared car (R$20-30), or a pre-arranged Lençóis→Capão transfer ~£15-£30 pp", "tip": "For Vale do Capão, the smarter routing is to take the bus toward Palmeiras (Real Expresso 'Ent. Palmeiras') rather than all the way to Lençóis, then the short dirt-road hop — confirm with your pousada who usually coordinate the Palmeiras pickup."}], "total": "Roughly 11-14 hours door-to-door (flight + airport transfer + 6-7h bus + final leg), so realistically a full travel day; budget an overnight in Salvador if you land after early afternoon.", "cost": "~£70-£135 pp total one-way (flight £40-90 + airport taxi share £7-12 + bus £20-24 + final leg £2-30). Group private transfer alternative below changes this.", "frequency": "Real Expresso/Rápido Federal run ~3-4 buses/day Salvador→Lençóis, typically morning (~08:00), early afternoon (~13:00) and a late night (~23:00-23:30) departure; daily, year-round. Salvador has frequent domestic flights from all major Brazilian hubs throughout the day.", "tips": ["Book the Salvador-Lençóis bus online (realexpresso.com.br, ClickBus or Busbud) at least a few days ahead in peak season (Dec-Feb, July, holidays) — the 3 daily departures sell out and a no-seat means losing a whole day.", "Sync your flight and bus: aim to land in Salvador before ~12:00 so you comfortably make the early-afternoon coach; otherwise take the morning bus the next day after a night near the rodoviária.", "For 5 people, price a private door-to-door transfer (Ivan Bahia, Discover Chapada, Bahia Transfer): ~R$2,850 for up to 4, so a larger van for 5 is roughly £100-£130 pp — only worth it if you value the time saved and direct Vale do Capão drop-off."], "gotchas": ["Vale do Capão is NOT reachable by the through bus — the last ~20-23 km from Palmeiras is unpaved (4x4-ish) dirt road; you must arrange a local car/van or pousada pickup, and it can be slow/impassable after heavy rain.", "Lençóis also has a tiny airport (LEC) but scheduled flights are sparse/seasonal and pricey (R$250-1,500) — don't count on flying direct to Chapada; the Salvador+bus combo is the reliable route.", "The late-night (~23:00) bus arrives in Lençóis pre-dawn; convenient for not losing a day but you arrive in the dark — pre-book a pousada that accepts early/overnight check-in."], "recommend": "Fly into Salvador on an early flight, take the morning Real Expresso semi-leito bus (~6-7h, ~£22pp) to Lençóis; for Vale do Capão, ride toward Palmeiras and have your pousada arrange the final dirt-road pickup."}, {"key": "reach-lencois", "title": "Reaching Lençóis Maranhenses (Atins base) for 5 men", "segments": [{"from": "São Paulo (GRU) or your Brazil hub", "to": "São Luís (SLZ) — Marechal Cunha Machado Intl", "mode": "flight", "detail": "LATAM, Gol or Azul. ~4 nonstop GRU-SLZ daily (LATAM most frequent, ~30/wk nonstop) plus Brasília (BSB) and Fortaleza (FOR) routings. SLZ is the only sensible air gateway to the park.", "duration": "3h nonstop from GRU (4-6h if connecting via BSB/FOR)", "cost": "£60-95 pp one-way (one-way fares from ~$90; book each leg of round-trip)", "tip": "Fly into SLZ, NOT out of a small Lençóis strip — flexibility and price are far better. Group of 5 fits one standard departure; book all 5 on the same flight so your São Luís transfer pickup is one pickup."}, {"from": "São Luís (SLZ airport / city)", "to": "Barreirinhas (gateway town)", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "~260 km, paved (MA-402 'Estrada dos Lençóis'). Shared minivan ~R$100-160 pp (operators: Kairós Tur, Rota Combo, TransferBarreirinhas.com, Guia Lençóis Maranhenses). For 5 men a private van (6-seat) is R$1,375-1,500 total day rate — works out cheaper/comfier than 5 shared seats and lets you set your own departure.", "duration": "approx 4 hours", "cost": "shared ~£15-25 pp; OR private 6-seat van ~£42-46 pp (R$1,375-1,500 total / 5)", "tip": "Shared departures cluster at ~06:45-08:00 and ~16:00-17:00. With 5 people just book the private van — door-to-door pickup at SLZ airport, no waiting to fill seats."}, {"from": "Barreirinhas", "to": "Atins (your dune-edge base) via beach/dunes", "mode": "4x4", "detail": "Open-top 'Toyota' 4x4 (jardineira / Land Cruiser) crosses river ferry then runs the beach-and-dune track. Operators: G.i Conect Viagens, Rota Combo, Divertix. Private Toyota for 1-10 pax ~R$1,500-1,645 total. Per-seat shared ~R$190 pp.", "duration": "approx 1h30 (tide-dependent)", "cost": "shared ~£29 pp; OR private Toyota ~£46-51 pp (R$1,500-1,645 total / 5)", "tip": "Runs ONLY at low tide — departure (often ~09:30 from the Correios/post office) shifts daily with the tide table. Confirm your slot against tides before committing to a same-day SLZ flight arrival."}], "total": "Realistically 1.5-2 days door-to-door from outside Brazil: ~3h flight + ~4h road + ~1.5h 4x4 = ~9-10h of pure transit, but tide windows on the Atins leg usually force an overnight in Barreirinhas. SLZ-to-Atins in one day is only possible with an early flight + favourable low tide.", "cost": "~£110-145 pp door-to-door using private vehicles (flight £60-95 + private van ~£44 + private Toyota ~£48). Shave to ~£85-115 pp if you take shared transfers throughout.", "frequency": "Flights to SLZ daily (multiple). São Luís-Barreirinhas shared transfers run twice daily (early AM ~06:45-08:00, late PM ~16:00-17:00); private on demand. Barreirinhas-Atins 4x4 runs ONLY at low tide, so daily departure time moves with the tide table.", "tips": ["Book the SLZ-Barreirinhas transfer and the Barreirinhas-Atins 4x4 2-3 days ahead in high season (July, Brazilian holidays, and the full-lagoon months Mar-May/Jun) — slots fill fast.", "Use one local operator (Kairós Tur, Rota Combo or G.i Conect) to chain both the van and the Toyota — they coordinate the tide timing and the river-ferry crossing for you.", "Pay attention to cash vs card: many Toyota/transfer quotes (e.g. R$1,500 cash) are 'à vista' cash prices; card or installments cost more. Carry some reais."], "gotchas": ["Barreirinhas has only a tiny airstrip (4-6 seat planes via SLZ agencies), NOT a commercial airport — do not plan scheduled flights into Barreirinhas; route via São Luís.", "The Atins 4x4 runs only at low tide; a late or delayed SLZ flight can make you miss the day's window and force an unplanned extra night in Barreirinhas.", "Atins is rustic — sandy streets, frequent power/wifi gaps, mostly cash. Sort accommodation and any onward dune-buggy tours before you arrive."], "recommend": "Fly into São Luís (SLZ), take a private 6-seat van to Barreirinhas (~4h), overnight there, then a private Toyota 4x4 to Atins at the next low tide — for 5 men, private vehicles cost barely more per head than shared seats and remove all the waiting and tide-timing stress."}, {"key": "reach-bonito", "title": "Reach Bonito (via Campo Grande, road transfer ~4h)", "segments": [{"from": "São Paulo (GRU/CGH) or other hub", "to": "Campo Grande Intl Airport (CGR)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "GOL, LATAM or Azul; ~1h50 nonstop from São Paulo. Several daily frequencies; CGR is the main gateway for Bonito.", "duration": "~1h50 flight (+1h airport)", "cost": "£40-75 one-way from São Paulo (R$260-490). Book early; high-season Jun-Sep dearer.", "tip": "For 5 men, fares drop sharply if booked 6-8 weeks out; compare CGH (Congonhas, central) vs GRU. Aim to land before midday to catch an afternoon transfer."}, {"from": "Campo Grande Airport (CGR)", "to": "Bonito (your pousada/hotel)", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "Shared van/minibus operators (Vanzella, Bonitour/Roteiro Fácil, Crisval, Acqua Viagens). 290 km, door-to-door drop at hotel, one meal/coffee stop. A private van for 5 is a good-value alternative to 5 shared seats.", "duration": "~4h30", "cost": "Shared ~£20/pp (R$130 one-way). Private van for the group ~£90-115 total (~£18-23pp).", "tip": "A rep holds a 'Vanzella' sign at arrivals. With 5 people, price a PRIVATE van — often similar total to 5 shared seats but flexible on timing and no extra stops."}], "total": "~7-8h door-to-door from São Paulo (1h50 flight + ~1h airport + 4h30 road + buffers)", "cost": "~£60-95 pp one-way (flight £40-75 + transfer £18-23)", "frequency": "Flights to CGR: several daily from São Paulo. Shared transfers from CGR depart roughly 10:00, 15:00, 17:00, 20:00 (plus a 23:30 run needing min 4 pax). Cruzeiro do Sul public bus is the cheap fallback: ~08:00, 14:00, 17:00 (~5h, R$95-130 / £15-20pp) but drops at Bonito bus station, not your hotel.", "tips": ["Pre-book the transfer online (Bonitour/Roteiro Fácil, Civitatis or directly with Vanzella) and give your flight number so they meet the flight — last-minute group seats can sell out.", "Line up flight arrival with a transfer departure window; landing before ~15:00 lets you take the afternoon van and arrive Bonito for dinner.", "For a private van, message 2-3 operators on WhatsApp for a group quote — they negotiate, especially low season."], "gotchas": ["Bonito's own airport (BYO) only has the seasonal Azul direct from Campinas (VCP), ~3x/week Tue/Thu/Sun, plus a GOL link — limited days/seats and pricier; don't assume daily flights into BYO. CGR + road is the reliable default.", "Shared transfer adds a meal/coffee stop, stretching the 4h drive toward 4h30-5h; budget the buffer.", "High season (Jun-Sep, school holidays) spikes both flight and transfer prices and fills vans — book the whole chain ahead.", "The public Cruzeiro do Sul bus is cheapest but terminates at Bonito's rodoviária, not your hotel — you'll need a local taxi/van on top."], "recommend": "Fly São Paulo→Campo Grande (CGR) then book a PRIVATE Vanzella/Bonitour van for the 5 of you (~4h30, hotel-door drop) — best balance of cost, comfort and flexibility."}, {"key": "reach-pantanal", "title": "Reach the Pantanal — North (Cuiabá + Transpantaneira) vs South (Campo Grande)", "segments": [{"from": "São Paulo (GRU)", "to": "Cuiabá (CGB)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "NORTH ROUTE. LATAM/GOL/Azul direct, ~2h45. Azul/LATAM cheapest one-ways often ~US$54-90", "duration": "2h45 + ~1.5h airport buffer", "cost": "£45-90 one-way", "tip": "Book an early/mid-morning arrival so you can drive the Transpantaneira in daylight and wildlife-spot en route"}, {"from": "Cuiabá / Poconé", "to": "Porto Jofre area lodge", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "NORTH ROUTE. ~249km, ~6h: ~1h paved to Poconé, then 137km unpaved Transpantaneira (~122 wooden bridges). Lodge van or 4x4", "duration": "~6h (4-6h depending on lodge)", "cost": "£60-90 pp shared (less when 5 split a private van)", "tip": "Refuel at Poconé — NO fuel, electricity or phone signal between there and Porto Jofre; the bridges and game-spotting are the highlight, not a chore"}, {"from": "São Paulo (GRU)", "to": "Campo Grande (CGR)", "mode": "flight", "detail": "SOUTH ROUTE (alternative). GOL/LATAM direct, ~1h45. GOL typically cheapest, one-ways from ~US$50", "duration": "1h45 + ~1.5h airport buffer", "cost": "£40-80 one-way", "tip": "Shorter flight than Cuiabá; good if pairing the trip with Bonito's clear-water snorkelling"}, {"from": "Campo Grande", "to": "South Pantanal lodge (Miranda/Aquidauana, via Estrada Parque)", "mode": "private transfer", "detail": "SOUTH ROUTE. ~5h30 to lodges; shared minivan to Buraco das Piranhas then lodge 4x4, or straight private car", "duration": "~5h30 (3h30 from Aquidauana, up to 7h for remote farms)", "cost": "£55-85 pp shared", "tip": "Dry season (Apr-Nov) allows the 4x4 road; in the Dec-Mar wet season some lodges are reachable only by small plane — confirm before booking"}], "total": "North route door-to-door from São Paulo (GRU): ~9-10h (≈2h45 flight + airport buffer + ~6h road to Porto Jofre). South route to a Miranda/Aquidauana lodge: ~8-9h (≈1h45 flight + ~5h30 road).", "cost": "North ~£110-160 pp (flight ~£45-90 one-way + shared road transfer ~£60-90 pp). South ~£100-150 pp (flight ~£40-80 + shared minivan/4x4 transfer ~£55-85 pp). Private vehicle for all 5 raises the road leg but splits well across the group.", "frequency": "Both legs depart São Paulo (GRU) many times daily. To Cuiabá (CGB): LATAM ~34, GOL ~17, Azul ~14 direct flights/week. To Campo Grande (CGR): LATAM ~27, GOL ~20 direct/week. Road transfers run on-demand or to lodge schedules; book the lodge transfer to match your flight arrival. Best wildlife window (dry season) is roughly July-October for the north.", "tips": ["Book the lodge package WITH its transfer included — Pantanal lodges almost always arrange the road leg, and a self-driven rental on the Transpantaneira's rough bridges is risky and slow for newcomers.", "Buy the GRU domestic flight on the Brazilian carrier sites (voegol.com.br, latam, voeazul) in BRL — fares are noticeably cheaper than aggregators, and a group of 5 should book together to keep seats on the same flight.", "Time the inbound long-haul (e.g. LHR→GRU on BA/LATAM, ~£720-930 return) to connect with a morning domestic departure, ideally overnighting in São Paulo to avoid a missed-connection if the international flight slips."], "gotchas": ["The Transpantaneira is unpaved with ~120+ ageing wooden bridges, no fuel and no phone signal past Poconé — never attempt it after dark or in a low-clearance car; allow the full 6h and carry water.", "Wet season (roughly Dec-Mar) floods both road routes; the southern Estrada Parque in particular can force a switch to costly small-plane charters — match your dates to the dry season for road access and best wildlife.", "'Reaching the Pantanal' for 5 men means 5x domestic fares plus a shared transfer, but a private vehicle is often only modestly more once split 5 ways and saves waiting for other guests — price both with the lodge."], "recommend": "For 5 men chasing jaguars on a lodge stay, go NORTH: fly São Paulo→Cuiabá, then a private van down the Transpantaneira to a Porto Jofre area lodge — Porto Jofre has the world's highest jaguar density and near-guaranteed dry-season sightings; take South (Campo Grande) only if you want easier roads, comfier farm-lodges and a Bonito add-on."}, {"key": "reach-salvador", "title": "Reach Salvador & Bahia (from Rio/São Paulo)", "segments": [{"from": "Rio de Janeiro (GIG/SDU)", "to": "Salvador (SSA)", "mode": "flight", "operator/detail": "GOL is the workhorse on this route (44 nonstop/week), LATAM the main alt (14/week). Azul mostly routes via connections. Nonstop GIG/SDU–SSA.", "detail": "GOL ~44 nonstop/week, LATAM ~14/week, both nonstop GIG/SDU–SSA; Azul mostly connecting", "duration": "1h 55m nonstop", "cost": "£45–£70 one-way (GOL from ~£45 / R$290; LATAM from ~£48)", "tip": "Book GOL out of Santos Dumont (SDU) if you can — it's in central Rio so you skip the long Galeao (GIG) schlep, though most SSA nonstops leave from GIG.", "cost_pp_gbp": "£45-70"}, {"from": "São Paulo (GRU/CGH)", "to": "Salvador (SSA)", "mode": "flight", "operator/detail": "Alternative origin. GOL (~97 nonstop/week), LATAM (~100/week) and Azul (~49/week) all fly nonstop daily.", "detail": "GOL ~97 nonstop/week, LATAM ~100/week, Azul ~49/week, all daily nonstop", "duration": "1h 55m–2h 25m nonstop", "cost": "£35–£60 one-way (GOL from ~£35 / R$230)", "tip": "São Paulo is consistently the cheapest gateway to SSA — GOL fares dip to ~R$230. If the group is splitting flights, route via SP not Rio to save ~£10pp.", "cost_pp_gbp": "£35-60"}, {"from": "Salvador airport (SSA)", "to": "Salvador centre / Pelourinho", "mode": "taxi", "operator/detail": "Uber or 99 app (safer + cheaper than rank taxis). Airport is 28km / 30–45 min from the historic centre.", "detail": "Uber/99 ~R$40–60; metered airport taxi R$80–120; BRT Aeroclassic exec bus is cheapest but drops at a terminal not your hotel", "duration": "30–45 min", "cost": "£6–£9 per car via Uber/99 (R$40–60), so ~£2–3pp split across the group", "tip": "For 5 men use two Ubers/99s or one UberXL — metered rank taxis charge nearly double. Afternoon traffic on the access road is heavy.", "cost_pp_gbp": "£2-3"}, {"from": "Salvador (Mercado Modelo nautical terminal)", "to": "Morro de São Paulo", "mode": "ferry", "operator/detail": "Catamaran across the Bay of All Saints. Operators: Ilha Bela, Biotur, Farol do Morro (Morro Lighthouse). Departs in front of Mercado Modelo.", "detail": "Catamaran ~R$113pp each way; departures ~08:30/09:00/10:30/13:00/14:30; ~2h30", "duration": "2h 30m", "cost": "~£17 one-way (R$113)", "tip": "This crossing of open bay water gets rough — take a Dramamine before boarding and sit at the back. In bad weather the lancha+van overland route via Valença is the backup.", "cost_pp_gbp": "£17"}, {"from": "Salvador airport (SSA)", "to": "Praia do Forte / Imbassaí (north coast beaches)", "mode": "bus", "operator/detail": "Alternative onward instead of Morro. Public line 1001 bus, or Atlântico Transportes coach. Private transfers also available.", "detail": "Line 1001 bus ~R$13 (£2), ~1h45 to Praia do Forte; private transfer ~R$60pp / EUR49–54 per group; Imbassaí ~2h via Atlântico Transportes", "duration": "1h 45m (Praia do Forte) – 2h (Imbassaí)", "cost": "£2 by bus, or ~£9–12pp by shared private transfer", "tip": "Praia do Forte (north) is the easy beach option — no boat needed, paved road. Choose this over Morro if anyone in the group is prone to seasickness.", "cost_pp_gbp": "£2-12"}], "total": "Door-to-door Rio/SP → Morro de São Paulo beach: roughly 7–9 hours (≈2h flight + airport/transfer + ferry timing buffer, since the last useful catamaran leaves Salvador ~14:30). Rio/SP → Praia do Forte: ~4–5 hours.", "cost": "≈£65–95 per person one-way door-to-door (cheapest = SP flight + bus to Praia do Forte ~£40; typical = Rio flight + Uber + Morro catamaran ~£70–90)", "frequency": "Flights daily and frequent from both Rio and SP (GOL/LATAM nonstop, multiple per day). Morro catamaran runs ~5 departures/day from Salvador, roughly 08:30–14:30 only — no late crossings, so arrange your flight to land before midday if connecting same-day to Morro.", "tips": ["Book domestic flights on GOL or LATAM's Brazilian sites (gol.com.br / latam.com Brazil) in BRL — fares are noticeably cheaper than the USD/GBP international storefronts, and a Brazilian card or Wise helps avoid markup.", "Buy the Morro de São Paulo catamaran ticket the day before from the Mercado Modelo terminal or via GetYourGuide/Bookaway to lock a morning slot — the early boats sell out and you don't want to miss the ~14:30 last departure.", "For 5 people, book flights early: domestic Brazilian fares climb steeply near departure and group seating gets scarce on the popular GOL frequencies."], "gotchas": ["The Salvador–Morro catamaran has no late departures (last ~14:30) — a delayed inbound flight can strand you in Salvador for the night, so don't book a tight same-day connection.", "The bay crossing to Morro is genuinely choppy and people get seasick; in rough weather the catamaran is cancelled and you must do the longer lancha + van route via Valença/Bom Despacho.", "Salvador centre and the airport area require normal big-city caution — use Uber/99 (tracked) rather than hailing street taxis, especially at night."], "recommend": "Fly GOL nonstop from São Paulo (cheapest, ~£35–45, 2h), split two Ubers to the centre, and take the morning catamaran to Morro de São Paulo — or skip the boat for Praia do Forte by bus if seasickness is a worry."}], "overview": {"flights": {"airlines": ["GOL Linhas Aereas - largest domestic network, Boeing 737 fleet, hub at GRU/GIG/BSB; reliable for trunk routes Rio-Sao Paulo-Brasilia-Salvador-Recife", "LATAM Brasil - widest network incl. international; generally the most comfortable hard product, frequent on big routes", "Azul - strongest in smaller/regional cities (uses turboprops + Embraer jets) so often the ONLY option to off-the-beaten-track destinations; hubs at Campinas (VCP) and Belo Horizonte (CNF)"], "baggage": "All three: 1 free carry-on (overhead) + 1 personal item on every fare. GOL/LATAM carry-on ~10kg, linear sum 115cm; Azul carry-on 10kg, 55x35x25cm (Azul allows 2 cabin bags). CHECKED BAG IS NOT FREE on the cheapest fares - GOL 'Light', LATAM 'Basic', Azul 'Azul' fares are carry-on only. First checked bag (23kg) costs roughly R$60-80 if added online in advance vs R$80-120 at the airport; Azul ~R$30 online / R$50 airport for extra pieces. Mid-tier fares (GOL 'Plus', LATAM 'Light/Plus', Azul 'Mais Azul') bundle 1 free 23kg bag + free seat selection. Excess over 23kg ~R$25-30/kg. For 5 men: either travel carry-on only, or buy the fare that includes the bag - adding bags a la carte for 5 people gets expensive fast.", "booking": "Book 6-8 weeks out for best prices (LATAM says sweet spot is 2-6 months before; last-minute is dear). Use the airline apps directly (Voe Gol, LATAM, Voe Azul) - they often beat aggregators and let you pick bundled fares. Compare on Google Flights / Skyscanner / Kayak first, then book on the airline app. Foreign Visa/Mastercard work fine; you do NOT need a CPF to buy (use passport). A 5-person booking is fine but fares are per-seat dynamic - book all together so you don't get split across fare buckets.", "fares": "Typical one-way domestic economy (carry-on only): short/popular hops Rio-Sao Paulo ~R$150-350 (£23-54); medium e.g. Sao Paulo-Salvador/Recife ~R$300-600 (£46-92); long-haul north (Manaus, Foz do Iguacu, Fortaleza) ~R$400-900 (£62-138). Add ~R$60-120 each way per person if you need a checked bag. Round trips R$400-1200 (£62-185) depending on route/timing.", "tips": ["Avoid Jan/early Feb (summer school holidays), July (winter break), Carnaval (Feb 2027 but check), and long-weekend national holidays - fares spike. Sep-Oct 2026 is a good low-season window with cheaper seats.", "Fly mid-week (Tue/Wed) and off-peak hours for the lowest fares; very early or late flights are cheapest.", "For 5 people, carry-on-only is the big money saver - one shared checked bag for shared gear rather than five.", "Azul is often the only carrier to smaller airports - check it specifically if going beyond the main cities.", "Domestic flights frequently beat 12-24h overnight buses on price-per-time for long distances (e.g. Rio to the Northeast)."]}, "buses": {"operators": ["Cometa - JCA group, premium fleet, strong on Sao Paulo-Rio, SP-Curitiba, SP-Santos, BH-Rio corridors", "1001 (Auto Viacao 1001) - also JCA group, dominant on Rio <-> Espirito Santo / coast and Rio-SP", "Util - Minas Gerais routes (Rio/SP to Belo Horizonte region)", "Costa Verde - the go-to for the Green Coast: Rio <-> Paraty <-> Angra dos Reis and on to SP", "Catarinense / Penha / Itapemirim Suzantur - south and coastal routes", "Gontijo / Aguia Branca / Expresso Guanabara - long-haul interior and Northeast"], "booking": "Use ClickBus (clickbus.com.br) - the biggest aggregator, 300+ companies, 4,800+ destinations, has an English-ish interface and accepts foreign cards/PayPal. Buser (buser.com.br) is the other major app, often slightly cheaper but Portuguese-only. For the Rio-Paraty-Angra Green Coast, you can book Costa Verde direct on its site/app. Busbud and Bookaway are foreigner-friendly fallbacks that accept passport + foreign card if a Brazilian site demands a CPF (you can usually leave CPF blank or enter zeros, but these aggregators avoid the issue). Book a few days ahead for popular overnight routes - lie-flat seats sell out, window seats first.", "comfort": "Three classes: Convencional/Executivo (reclining ~110-130deg airline-style), Semi-Leito (more recline + legrest), and Leito/Leito-Cama (near-180deg lie-flat with legrest, blanket, pillow - only ~8-10 per bus). For overnight intercity (e.g. Sao Paulo-Foz do Iguacu ~16h, SP-Rio ~6h overnight), pay up for Leito/Leito-Cama: it replaces a hotel night and is genuinely comfortable. Buses have AC (bring a layer - they run cold), onboard toilet, and stop at roadside stations every few hours.", "tips": ["A one-way Leito-cama overnight runs roughly R$150-450 (~£23-69) depending on distance - SP-Rio cheaper end, long Northeast hauls dearer.", "For 5 men, the lie-flat Leito on overnight routes saves 5 hotel beds while you travel - good budget math.", "Buy aisle+window pairs early; for a group of 5 you'll likely be split across rows on a leito bus (lower deck has few seats).", "AC is aggressive - pack a hoodie and long trousers for overnight legs.", "Major rodoviarias (Tiete in Sao Paulo, Novo Rio) are huge - arrive 30-45 min early and watch your bags."]}, "money": {"cash": "Brazil is near-cashless - cards work ~99% of the time. Carry only a small float of ~R$100-200 per person (~£15-30) for the rare cash-only kiosk, beach vendor, small-town bus station, or tip. Withdraw reais from Banco24Horas / Banco do Brasil / Bradesco ATMs (avoid Euronet machines - poor rates/high fees). Never rely on exchanging GBP cash.", "cards": "Bring contactless Visa/Mastercard - accepted almost everywhere including taxis, market stalls, and most buses/apps. Use a no-FX-fee card (Wise, Revolut, Monzo, Chase) to avoid ~3% loading. Carry two different cards across the group in case one is blocked. Apple Pay / Google Pay widely accepted.", "transferApps": "Ride-hailing: Uber and 99 (99 is the local one, often cheaper, also does motorbike '99 Moto') both take foreign cards in-app - use these over street taxis for fair pricing and safety. inDrive and Cabify also available. Intercity bus booking: ClickBus app (foreigner-friendly, foreign cards/PayPal) and Buser (cheaper, Portuguese-only); Costa Verde app for the Green Coast. Flights: Voe Gol, LATAM, and Voe Azul apps.", "cash_note": "Pix (instant bank transfer, QR-based) is everywhere but normally needs a Brazilian CPF + bank account, so tourists can't use the native version. Workaround: apps like Wallbit (or some Wise/Nomad setups) let foreigners pay Pix QR codes without a CPF - useful for vendors who only take Pix - but a contactless card covers nearly everything, so Pix is optional, not essential.", "tipping": "Tipping is modest and not a big-tip culture. Restaurants add a 10% 'servico' (couvert/service) to the bill automatically - paying it is customary and that's it, no extra needed. No tipping expected for Uber/99, taxis, tour guides, or hotel staff beyond rounding up or a few reais for genuinely good service. Bars: the 10% is usually on the tab.", "cards_apps_summary": "Set up Uber + 99 + ClickBus before you fly and get an eSIM (Airalo/Holafly) so you have data on landing to call rides and book buses immediately."}}};